      "concept": "Exudate Types; Wound Infection",
      "unitId": 3,
      "questionText": "A nurse is assessing a postoperative client's abdominal incision on the second day after surgery. The nurse notes that the wound has thick, opaque, yellow-green drainage with a foul odor. Which action should the nurse take first?",
      "options": [
        { "id": "A", "text": "Document the finding and continue to monitor every 4 hours" },
        { "id": "B", "text": "Apply a clean dressing and reassess in 8 hours" },
        { "id": "C", "text": "Obtain a wound culture and notify the provider" },
        { "id": "D", "text": "Irrigate the wound with hydrogen peroxide to reduce bacteria" }
      ],
      "correctIds": ["C"],
      "correctAnswerText": "C",
      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect:** Thick, opaque, yellow-green, malodorous drainage is purulent and indicates wound infection. Simply documenting and monitoring without intervention is inadequate and delays necessary treatment.\n\n❌ **B — Incorrect:** Applying a clean dressing without addressing the underlying infection does not treat the problem and allows the infection to worsen.\n\n✅ **C — Correct:** Purulent drainage with foul odor are classic signs of wound infection. The nurse should obtain a wound culture (before starting antibiotics, if possible) to identify the organism and guide treatment, then notify the provider for further orders including antibiotics, wound care changes, and possible surgical consultation.\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect:** Hydrogen peroxide is cytotoxic to fibroblasts and epithelial cells and is not appropriate for wound cleansing. It damages the wound bed and delays healing. It should not be used for wound irrigation.\n\n---",
