      "unitId": 9,
      "questionText": "A nurse is assessing two clients with lower extremity ulcers. Client A has a wound on the medial ankle with moderate exudate, edema, and reports that the pain is relieved when the leg is elevated. Client B has a wound on the lateral ankle and toes with minimal drainage, cool skin, and reports pain that worsens with leg elevation. Which interpretation of these findings is correct?",
      "options": [
        { "id": "A", "text": "Both clients have venous ulcers and both should receive compression therapy" },
        { "id": "B", "text": "Client A has a venous ulcer; Client B has an arterial ulcer" },
        { "id": "C", "text": "Client A has an arterial ulcer; Client B has a venous ulcer" },
        { "id": "D", "text": "Both clients have arterial ulcers and require immediate vascular surgery referral" }
      ],
      "correctIds": ["B"],
      "correctAnswerText": "B",
      "explanation": "**Rationales:**\n\n❌ **A — Incorrect:** Client B's presentation (lateral/toe location, minimal drainage, cool skin, pain worsened by elevation) is classic arterial insufficiency. Applying compression therapy to an arterial ulcer can reduce perfusion further and cause limb ischemia.\n\n✅ **B — Correct:** Client A demonstrates classic venous ulcer characteristics: medial ankle location, moderate exudate, edema, and pain relief with elevation (elevation reduces venous hypertension). Client B demonstrates classic arterial ulcer characteristics: lateral/toe location, minimal drainage, cool skin, and ischemic pain that worsens with elevation (elevation further reduces arterial blood flow to the extremity).\n\n❌ **C — Incorrect:** This reverses the correct assessment findings.\n\n❌ **D — Incorrect:** Client A's presentation is not consistent with arterial disease.\n\n---",
      "isSATA": false
